items.standfirst: The doctor was left to die on the ground after being stabbed six times.
items.content: A teen who murdered a beloved Melbourne GP has been jailed for 17 years for brutally stabbing an unarmed man.The boy, now 18, looked straight ahead as Victorian Supreme Court Justice Amanda Fox handed down his sentence this morning.A jury found he murdered doctor Ashley Gordon near his Doncaster home in Melbourne's north-east early on January 13, 2024.READ MORE: Hundreds of jobs on the line as caravan maker collapsesThe teen and a friend broke into the house about 4am, stealing shoes, headphones, laptops, a wallet and silver necklaces.They went back to a nearby house party before returning to Gordon's house, planning to steal the Mercedes-Benz that was parked in the garage.Gordon caught them as they tried to break in a second time, chasing the teens onto the street and then following them in his car.READ MORE: Trump gives green light to release MRI resultsHe got out of the vehicle once they reached a nearby street and the doctor tried to restrain the then-16-year-old, telling him the police were on their way.But the boy pulled out a knife and stabbed Gordon six times before leaving him to die on the ground.Justice Fox described the murder as a brutal attack against an unarmed man as she sentenced the teen to 17 years' jail.READ MORE: Australia's happiest generation of workers revealedHe will be eligible for parole after 12 years.Gordon's family and friends let out a gasp and then cried as the sentence was handed down.DOWNLOAD THE 9NEWS APP: Stay across all the latest in breaking news, sport, politics and the weather via our news app and get notifications sent straight to your smartphone. items.title: Man dies, another injured in retaining wall collapse in Brisbane
items.standfirst: Queensland Ambulance Service confirmed two patients are being treated for significant injuries, including one patient who is entrapped after a retaining wall collapsed on Boundary Street in Brisbane's West End.
items.content: A man has died and another has been injured after a retaining wall collapsed in Brisbane's West End this morning. Queensland Ambulance Service confirmed two patients suffered significant injuries when a retaining wall collapsed on Boundary Street in the inner -southern suburb just before 8.30am.A 45-year-old man was in a life-threatening condition when paramedics arrived and died at the scene. A 19-year-old man was also injured and has been taken to the Royal Brisbane and Women's Hospital in a stable condition after a "prolonged extrication" that took more than an hour.The younger man was trapped from the waist down and was assisted by other workers on the scene who helped move rubble to allow paramedics to reach him. Police are also on the scene and have described it as a workplace incident.Workplace Health and Safety will investigate. Boundary Street is currently closed between Melbourne Street and Edmondstone Street and motorists are advised to avoid the area.More to come.
